subSection.paragraph:
The 16S and COI sequences obtained for
Amathia reptopinnata
n. sp.
were aligned with those from other bryozoans deposited in GenBank ( Table 1 ) using Clustal W (
Thompson et al . 1994
) implemented in MEGA6.06 (
Tamura et al . 2013
). The alignment was performed gene by gene. Most of the sites for both 16S and COI were unambiguously aligned. We therefore used the entire region, excluding gap sites, for our phylogenetic analyses. For the COI dataset, we tested the substitution saturation at 1st + 2nd and 3rd codon positions with DAMBE (
Xia et al . 2003
), with only fully resolved sites.

Maximum likelihood (ML) analyses were performed with MEGA 6.06. The best-fit model for the 16S and COI sequences determined by the AICc implemented in MEGA 6.06 were GTR+G (general time reversible [
Tavaré 1986
] with gamma-distributed rates) and GTR+G+I (general time reversible [
Tavaré 1986
] with gamma-distributed rates and invariant rates among sites), respectively. We also analysed the 16S and COI sequences as a concatenated data set; the best-fit model for the 16S + COI data set determined by the AICc implemented in MEGA 6.06 was GTR+G+I. Optimal ML trees were found by a tree-bisection reconnection (
TBR
) search, starting with a tree topology generated by the BIONJ method (
Gascuel 1997
) using maximum composite likelihood (MCL) distances (

Tamura 
et al
. 2004

). One-thousand bootstrap pseudoreplicates were analysed to obtain nodal support values.

